1.d4 {Annotations by Semion Alapin} d5 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 Be7
{According to Alapin's annotations, this novelty avoids the
move order of 3...Nf6 4.Bg5 Be7 5.e3, and leads the game into
unfamiliar territory.} 4.e4 dxe4 5.Nxe4 Nf6 6.Ng3 c5 7.Nf3 Nc6
8.Be3 cxd4 9.Nxd4 Bb4+ 10.Ke2 Nxd4+ {10...Qc7 is probably
better} 11.Qxd4 Qxd4 12.Bxd4 Bd7 13.f3 Bc6 14.a3 Be7 15.b4 a6
16.Ke3 O-O 17.Bd3 Rfe8 {!} 18.Ne4 Nxe4 19.Bxe4 Bg5+ 20.f4 {?
20.Kf2 is equal} e5 {!} 21.Bxc6 Bxf4+ 22.Kf3 bxc6 23.Be3 Bxe3
24.Kxe3 f5 25.Rhf1 g6 26.g4 f4+ {!} 27.Ke4 Kf7 28.Rad1 Ke6
29.Rd3 Red8 30.Rfd1 Rxd3 31.Rxd3 Ra7 {! To counter the threat
32.c5 with ...Rd7.} 32.Rd8 Rf7 33.Re8+ Kd7 34.Ra8 Rf6 {!}
35.Ra7+ Kc8 36.Ra8+ Kc7 37.Ra7+ {If 33.Kxe5 f3! or 37.Kf3
e4+!.} Kb6 38.Rd7 f3 39.c5+ Kb5 40.Rd1 f2 41.Rf1 Ka4 42.Kxe5
Rf8 43.Kd6 Kxa3 44.Kxc6 Kxb4 45.Kd6 {! A master move! If
45.Kb6, Black wins easily, going with the king to e2} Kc3
46.c6 Kd3 47.Ke7 Rf4 {! 47...Ke2? 48.Rxf2+!.} 48.c7 Rc4
49.Rxf2 Rxc7+ 50.Kd6 Rc2 51.Rf3+ Ke4 52.Rh3 Kf4 53.Rxh7 Kxg4
54.h4 Rb2 {!} 55.Rh6 {55.Rg7? Kxh4! or 55.Kc6 Rf2 56.Kb6 Rf6+
57.Ka5 Rf5+ 58.Kxa6 Rh5 and Black wins} Kf5 56.h5 g5 57.Ke7
Rb7+ 58.Kf8 Kg4 {!} 59.Ke8 a5 60.Kd8 a4 61.Kc8 Ra7 0-1